60.7	Gypsum	Gypsum	Gypsum is a very soft sulfate mineral composed of calcium sulfate dihydrate, with the chemical formula CaSO4Â·2H2O. It is found in alabaster, a decorative stone used in Ancient Egypt. It is the second softest mineral on the Mohs Hardness Scale. It forms as an evaporite mineral and as a hydration product of anhydrite.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/SeleniteGypsumUSGOV.jpg/240px-SeleniteGypsumUSGOV.jpg
